      <div xml:id="NA129-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu pirivuṇarttappaṭṭa tōḻi talaimakaḷai mukampukkatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how the confidante who had been informed of the separation approached HER for a favour.</p>
      </div>
      <div xml:id="NA129">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            perunakai kēḷāy tōḻi kātala</l>
<l>            rorunāḷ kaḻiyiṉu muyirvēṟu paṭūum</l>
<l>            pomma lōti nammiva ṇoḻiyac</l>
<l>            celpa veṉpa tāmē ceṉṟu</l>
<l>            tamviṉai muṟṟi varūumvarai nammaṉai </l>
<l>            vāḻtu meṉpa nāmē yataṉṟalaik</l>
<l>            kēḻkiḷa rutti yaravuttalai paṉippap</l>
<l>            paṭumaḻai yurumi ṉuraṟṟukura</l>
<l>            ṉaṭunāḷ yāmattun tamiyaṅ kēṭṭē.</l>
            </lg>
       <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Hear the great joke<note place="foot">This quasi formula with nakai at the beginning of the poem is a little strange in the context. Either we take it as a formula slightly worn out, without much semantic impact here apart from arousing attention for a message to the confidante, or we take it as a bitter sarcasm: the confidante is to hear what started as joking between the lovers. Thirdly, we might also consider a semantic shift from "joke" to something like "incongruity".</note>, friend.</l>
<l rend="indent4">[Our] lover,</l>
<l>he himself says he will go</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that we with thick hair stay behind here,</l>
<l rend="indent3">where, even if one day passes by, life will be different.</l>
<l>When he is gone, we, he says, will be living in our house,</l>
<l rend="indent2">until he comes when his work is completed.</l>
<l rend="indent3">On top of that</l>
<l>we['ll be] alone even at midnight, hearing in the middle of the night</l>
<l rend="indent">the voice: thunder roaring with the falling rain,</l>
<l rend="indent2">so that the head of the snake with spotted hood shining with lustre</l>
<l rend="indent3">shivers.</l>
        </lg>
